SIMPLE: trident
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trident
<hw>Tri"dent</hw> <pr>(tr⟦imac⟧"d⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>tridens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>; <ets>tri-</ets> (see
<er>Tri-</er>) + <ets>dens</ets> tooth: cf. F. <ets>trident</ets>. See
<er>Tooth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class Myth.)</fld> <def>A kind
of scepter or spear with three prongs, -- the common attribute of
Neptune.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A three-pronged spear or
goad, used for urging horses; also, the weapon used by one class of
gladiators.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A three-pronged fish spear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A curve of third order, having
three infinite branches in one direction and a fourth infinite branch in
the opposite direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trident bat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an Asiatic
rhinolophid bat (<spn>Triaenops Persicus</spn>), having the nose
membrane in the shape of a trident.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trident</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trident
<hw>Tri"dent</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tridens</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Having three teeth or prongs; tridentate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tridentated</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Tridentate</ent>⟦br⟧
